<h2 class="wp-block-heading faq-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<div class="schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block"><div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1623393125914"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Are bodyweight exercises effective for runners?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Bodyweight exercises are valuable for runners when using proper form and applying targeted resistance on the working muscles. They are low-impact but still elicit maximum muscle engagement for strength gains. Focus on contracting the active muscles for best results.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1733375258337"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Do bodyweight exercises build endurance?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Bodyweight exercises are effective at building endurance as they allow for longer holds during the contraction phases. By using gradual, controlled movements and pausing while the muscles are contracted, you will stimulate adaptations that build muscle endurance.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1733375258948"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Are full-body workouts good for runners?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Full-body workouts are great for runners as they engage the major muscle groups used while running. Programming <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5889786/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">2â€“3 full-body workouts</a> a week will effectively strengthen all major muscle groups to improve running performance and reduce injuries.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1733375259514"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Should runners cut or bulk?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Runners should prioritize a balanced diet with regular strength training. Avoid cutting as this could cause under-fueling leading to illness or injury. Bulking is best done during the off-season to maximize lean muscle gain for performance benefits when training starts.</p> </div> </div>
